<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Biology" id="111" name="Transport in Plants">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Means of transport includes diffusion which is a ____ process.</text>
            <option id="A">Passive</option><option id="B">Active</option><option id="C">Chemical</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>No energy expenditure required.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which transport requires specific membrane proteins but NO energy?</text>
            <option id="A">Facilitated diffusion</option><option id="B">Simple diffusion</option><option id="C">Active transport</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Transport along concentration gradient via channels.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Active transport uses energy to pump molecules ____ concentration gradient.</text>
            <option id="A">Against</option><option id="B">Along</option><option id="C">Across only</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uphill transport requires ATP.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Water potential is denoted by the Greek symbol ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Psi (ψ)</option><option id="B">Phi (φ)</option><option id="C">Omega (ω)</option><option id="D">Delta (Δ)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard symbol for water energy potential.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pure water has a water potential of ____ at standard T and P.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">Max (positive)</option><option id="C">-100</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reference point for water potential scale.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Addition of solute ____ the water potential.</text>
            <option id="A">Lowers (makes it negative)</option><option id="B">Increases</option><option id="C">Doesn't change</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Solute potential (ψs) is always negative.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The pressure potential (ψp) is usually ____ in plants.</text>
            <option id="A">Positive</option><option id="B">Negative</option><option id="C">Zero</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to turgor pressure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Osmosis is diffusion of water across a ____ membrane.</text>
            <option id="A">Semi-permeable / Selectively permeable</option><option id="B">Impermeable</option><option id="C">Permeable</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Allows solvent but not all solutes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A cell placed in hypotonic solution will ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Swell</option><option id="B">Shrink</option><option id="C">Stay same</option><option id="D">Burst (if no wall)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water enters the cell.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Plasmolysis occurs when cell is placed in ____ solution.</text>
            <option id="A">Hypertonic</option><option id="B">Hypotonic</option><option id="C">Isotonic</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water leaves cell, cytoplasm shrinks away from wall.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Diffusion of water into seeds causing swelling is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Imbibition</option><option id="B">Osmosis</option><option id="C">Plasmolysis</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adsorption of water by solids.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Long distance transport of substances through vascular tissues is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Translocation</option><option id="B">Diffusion</option><option id="C">Active transport</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Via Xylem and Phloem.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Xylem transports water and minerals from ____ to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Roots, Leaves</option><option id="B">Leaves, Roots</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unidirectional upward flow.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phloem transports food materials from ____ to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Source, Sink</option><option id="B">Roots, Leaves only</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Multidirectional flow depending on need.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>System of interconnected protoplasts in plants is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Symplast</option><option id="B">Apoplast</option><option id="C">Tonoplast</option><option id="D">Chloroplast</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Movement through plasmodesmata.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>System of adjacent cell walls and intercellular spaces is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Apoplast</option><option id="B">Symplast</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Non-living path of transport.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Casparian strips in endodermis are made of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Suberin (impermeable to water)</option><option id="B">Cellulose</option><option id="C">Lignin</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forces water into symplastic path.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Evaporative loss of water by plants is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Transpiration</option><option id="B">Guttation</option><option id="C">Respiration</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mainly through stomata.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Opening and closing of stomata is due to turgidity of ____ cells.</text>
            <option id="A">Guard</option><option id="B">Mesophyll</option><option id="C">Epidermal</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specialized kidney/dumb-bell shaped cells.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Transpiration pull theory is also called ____ theory.</text>
            <option id="A">Cohesion-Tension</option><option id="B">Pressure Flow</option><option id="C">Vital Force</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proposed by Dixon and Jolly.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mutual attraction between water molecules is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cohesion</option><option id="B">Adhesion</option><option id="C">Surface Tension</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hydrogen bonding property.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Attraction of water molecules to polar surfaces like tracheary elements is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Adhesion</option><option id="B">Cohesion</option><option id="C">Guttation</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sticking to walls.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Water molecules attracted to each other in liquid phase more than gaseous is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Surface tension</option><option id="B">Capillarity</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Creates high tensile strength.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Loss of liquid droplets from leaf margins is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Guttation</option><option id="B">Transpiration</option><option id="C">Exudation</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs at night/early morning via hydathodes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Guttation is caused by ____ pressure.</text>
            <option id="A">Root</option><option id="B">Negative</option><option id="C">Atmospheric</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Positive hydrostatic pressure in xylem.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mineral absorption is mostly ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Active</option><option id="B">Passive</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Molecules move against gradient into root.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sucrose is loaded into phloem sieve tubes via ____ transport.</text>
            <option id="A">Active</option><option id="B">Passive</option><option id="C">Diffusion</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Requires energy at the source.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Movement in phloem follows ____ hypothesis.</text>
            <option id="A">Mass Flow / Pressure Flow</option><option id="B">Relay Pump</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proposed by Munch.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Unloading of phloem at sink requires ____ transport.</text>
            <option id="A">Active</option><option id="B">Passive</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Removing sucrose from sieve tubes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phloem cells associated with sieve tubes are ____ cells.</text>
            <option id="A">Companion</option><option id="B">Parenchyma</option><option id="C">Fiber</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Help in loading/unloading.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Direction of movement in Xylem is always ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Unidirectional (Upward)</option><option id="B">Bidirectional</option><option id="C">Multidirectional</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Roots to shoots only.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Stomata are generally open during ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Day</option><option id="B">Night</option><option id="C">Midday only</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>For photosynthesis / gas exchange.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element is associated with opening of stomata?</text>
            <option id="A">Potassium (K+)</option><option id="B">Sodium</option><option id="C">Calcium</option><option id="D">Magnesium</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>K+ malate theory of stomatal movement.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Atmospheric humidity ____ rate of transpiration.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreases</option><option id="B">Increases</option><option id="C">Stays same</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lower vapor pressure gradient.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Wind speed ____ rate of transpiration.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">Stays same</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Removes stagnant boundary layer of moisture.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Light ____ rate of transpiration.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases (via stomatal opening)</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Direct correlation with daytime activity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Main function of transpiration is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cooling and water transport</option><option id="B">Storing food</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Leaf temp can drop 10-15 degrees.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Plants minimize water loss using ____ adaptation in C4 plants.</text>
            <option id="A">Higher photosynthetic efficiency per water lost</option><option id="B">Closing stomata always</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C4 plants are twice as efficient as C3.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Root pressure can push water to ____ heights.</text>
            <option id="A">Small</option><option id="B">Tallest trees</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Insufficient for redwoods.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Transpiration pull can move water to ____ heights.</text>
            <option id="A">Great (up to 130m)</option><option id="B">Small</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sufficient for tallest trees.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Water potential of a solution is determined by ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ψs and ψp</option><option id="B">Na and K</option><option id="C">Light and heat</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ψw = ψs + ψp.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Solute potential (ψs) of a solution is always ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Negative</option><option id="B">Positive</option><option id="C">Zero</option><option id="D">Infinity</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Presence of solute decreases free energy of water.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pressure potential (ψp) is negative only in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Xylem during high transpiration</option><option id="B">Root cortex</option><option id="C">Phloem</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Suction / Tension state.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Turgor pressure matches ____ when cell is fully turgid.</text>
            <option id="A">Osmotic pressure</option><option id="B">Zero</option><option id="C">Suction pressure</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cell cannot take more water.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Movement of water into mycorrhizal fungi and then to root is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Symbiotic / Assisted apoplast</option><option id="B">Active only</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Fungal hyphae increase surface area.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dorsiventral leaves (dicot) have ____ stomata on lower surface.</text>
            <option id="A">More</option><option id="B">Less</option><option id="C">Equal</option><option id="D">Zero</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Typical dicot leaf structure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Isobilateral leaves (monocot) have ____ stomata on both surfaces.</text>
            <option id="A">Equal</option><option id="B">Unequal</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Typical grass/cereal leaf.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Tensile strength of water depends on ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cohesion, Adhesion, and Surface tension</option><option id="B">Color</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer>Allows thin columns to resist breaking.</question>
        <question>
            <text>Radial orientation of cellulose microfibrils in guard cells helps in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Opening of stomata</option><option id="B">Closing only</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Makes guard cells bend easier.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Essential minerals are absorbed as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ions</option><option id="B">Molecules only</option><option id="C">Gas</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Charged particles.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In phloem, sugar is transported as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sucrose</option><option id="B">Glucose</option><option id="C">Fructose</option><option id="D">Starch</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Non-reducing transport sugar.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Transport in phloem is from ____ to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Source to Sink</option><option id="B">Sink to Source</option><option id="C">Up to Down only</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Can reverse seasonally.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>During spring, sugar stored in roots moves to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Buds (emerging leaves)</option><option id="B">Soil</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Upward translocation example.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Experimental proof for phloem transport is ____ experiment.</text>
            <option id="A">Girdling / Ringing</option><option id="B">Bell jar</option><option id="C">Ganong's potometer</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Swelling above the ring due to blocked sap.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Movement of water through sieve tube is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Mass flow driven by pressure gradient</option><option id="B">Simple diffusion</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Munch's hypothesis mechanism.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Water which is available to the plants for absorption is ____ water.</text>
            <option id="A">Capillary</option><option id="B">Gravitational</option><option id="C">Hygroscopic</option><option id="D">Chemical</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Held in small soil pores.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Force of attraction between surface molecules is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Surface tension</option><option id="B">Adhesion</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Physical property of liquid water.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Diffusion pressure deficit (DPD) is also known as ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Suction pressure</option><option id="B">Turgor pressure</option><option id="C">Osmotic pressure only</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Demand for water.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>DPD of a flaccid cell is equal to its ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Osmotic pressure (OP)</option><option id="B">Zero</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>TP is zero in flaccid cell.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Movement of water always occurs from ____ DPD to ____ DPD.</text>
            <option id="A">Lower, Higher</option><option id="B">Higher, Lower</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>From low demand to high demand.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Movement of water occurs from ____ ψw to ____ ψw.</text>
            <option id="A">Higher, Lower</option><option id="B">Lower, Higher</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>High energy to low energy.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Imbibition is a type of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Diffusion</option><option id="B">Active transport</option><option id="C">Respiration</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Across a gradient without membrane.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Absorption of water by seeds creates ____ pressure.</text>
            <option id="A">Imbibition</option><option id="B">Osmotic</option><option id="C">Root</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Enough to split rocks.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Xylem vessels and tracheids are ____ at maturity.</text>
            <option id="A">Dead</option><option id="B">Living</option><option id="C">Photosynthetic</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>LUMEN is empty for flow.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Movement through xylem is ____ than phloem? No. Both are mass flows.</text>
            <option id="A">Dependent on pressure gradients</option><option id="B">Zero</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mass flow characteristic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hydathodes are also called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Water stomata</option><option id="B">Guard cells</option><option id="C">Lenticels</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Permanent openings at tips.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Potometer measures the rate of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Transpiration</option><option id="B">Photosynthesis</option><option id="C">Respiration</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Actually measures water uptake (proxy for transpiration).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Internal factor affecting transpiration:</text>
            <option id="A">Stomatal frequency</option><option id="B">Humidity</option><option id="C">Temperature</option><option id="D">Wind</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Plant-owned characteristic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Canal-like movement through plasmodesmata is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Symplastic</option><option id="B">Apoplastic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Through living bridge.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Endodermis is a major ____ for solute transport.</text>
            <option id="A">Check point / Control point</option><option id="B">Storage area</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specific transport proteins here.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The concentration of minerals is ____ in soil compared to inside root.</text>
            <option id="A">Lower (usually)</option><option id="B">Higher</option><option id="C">Equal</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forces active uptake.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Remobilization of minerals occurs from ____ to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Older leaves (senescent), younger leaves</option><option id="B">Soil, Root</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>P, S, N, K are mobile.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which element is structurally bound and NOT remobilized?</text>
            <option id="A">Calcium (Ca)</option><option id="B">Nitrogen</option><option id="C">Potassium</option><option id="D">Phosphorus</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Constituent of cell wall (pectates).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Loading at phloem source creates a ____ state.</text>
            <option id="A">Hypertonic</option><option id="B">Hypotonic</option><option id="C">Isotonic</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>High sucrose concentration draws water into phloem.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Water used in phloem move comes from ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Adjacent xylem</option><option id="B">Environment</option><option id="C">Cytoplasm</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proximity allows water exchange.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Transport of water, minerals and gases is ____ than transport of organic solutes? No.</text>
            <option id="A">Equally vital</option><option id="B">Irrelevant</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Balanced physiology.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Smallest distance diffusion can travel effectively is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Over a few cells</option><option id="B">Across whole plant</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Extremely slow for long distances.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>10 cm diffusion would take approx ____ years.</text>
            <option id="A">Years (based on physics)</option><option id="B">Seconds</option><option id="C">Minutes</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highlights need for mass flow.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Porins are proteins that form ____ in membranes.</text>
            <option id="A">Large pores</option><option id="B">Small pumps</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>In plastids, mitochondria, bacteria.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Symports move two molecules in ____ directions.</text>
            <option id="A">Same</option><option id="B">Opposite</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Co-transport type.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Antiports move two molecules in ____ directions.</text>
            <option id="A">Opposite</option><option id="B">Same</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Counter-transport.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Water channels (Aquaporins) are made of ____ different types of proteins.</text>
            <option id="A">8</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">100</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specific membrane complexes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Ψw of a plasmolyzed cell is ____ than its environment? No.</text>
            <option id="A">Lower (until equilibrium)</option><option id="B">Higher</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Driving water out.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pressure of 0.4MPa applied to a solution (psi_s = -0.5MPa). Resulting psi_w is:</text>
            <option id="A">-0.1 MPa</option><option id="B">0.9 MPa</option><option id="C">0.1 MPa</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>-0.5 + 0.4 = -0.1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>At equilibrium, cell ψw matched solution ψw. If external is -10 bar, cell is:</text>
            <option id="A">-10 bar</option><option id="B">0 bar</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Equilibrium definition.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which part of root is mostly used for symplastic movement of water into xylem?</text>
            <option id="A">Endodermis (Casparian barrier bypass)</option><option id="B">Cortex only</option><option id="C">Epidermis</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Final forced entry.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cohesion tension theory explains ____ pressure at top of plant.</text>
            <option id="A">Negative</option><option id="B">Positive</option><option id="C">Zero</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pulling force creates tension.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Transpiration ____ CO2 supply to leaves.</text>
            <option id="A">Ensures (via open stomata)</option><option id="B">Blocks</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Necessary trade-off for photosynthesis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>C4 plants use ____ the water as C3 for same amount of CO2 fixed.</text>
            <option id="A">Half</option><option id="B">Double</option><option id="C">Equal</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water use efficiency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bulk movement through sieve tubes is facilitated by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrostatic pressure gradient</option><option id="B">Gravity</option><option id="C">Capillarity</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Core of Pressure Flow theory.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Movement in Phloem is essentially ____ according to direction.</text>
            <option id="A">Source to Sink (Dynamic)</option><option id="B">Static</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Direction changes with seasonal needs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cell A (psi_s = -10, psi_p = 5), Cell B (psi_s = -15, psi_p = 5). Water moves:</text>
            <option id="A">A to B</option><option id="B">B to A</option><option id="C">No move</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>psi_w_A = -5, psi_w_B = -10. High to Low.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>When do stomata close during water stress?</text>
            <option id="A">Release of ABA (Abscisic Acid)</option><option id="B">Increase in K+</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stress hormone signal.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The velocity of mass flow in phloem is approx ____ cm/hr.</text>
            <option id="A">1 to 100</option><option id="B">0.001</option><option id="C">10000</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Measurable and significant.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Root pressure is highest during ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Early morning / Night with low transpiration</option><option id="B">Midday solar peak</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>When water is available but not escaping.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Tracheids and vessels are optimized for ____ flow.</text>
            <option id="A">Long-distance hydraulic conductance</option><option id="B">Photosynthesis</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Physical structure suits bulk movement.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Presence of lignin in walls prevents ____ during high tension.</text>
            <option id="A">Collapsing of vessels</option><option id="B">Bursting</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Structural support for negative pressure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Opening of stomata is an ____ process? No, indirectly active.</text>
            <option id="A">Requires Turgor change via ion pumping</option><option id="B">Passive solely</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Energy needed for K+ gradient.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A cell with ψw = -15 units. Placed in -10 units solution. Cell will ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Swell (gain water)</option><option id="B">Shrink</option><option id="C">Stay same</option><option id="D">Burst</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>External potential is higher.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>DPD of a turgid cell is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero</option><option id="B">OP</option><option id="C">TP</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>OP = TP, so DPD = 0.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Imbibition capacity depends on ____ of the material.</text>
            <option id="A">Hydrophilicity</option><option id="B">Color</option><option id="C">Size</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Attraction for water.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Starch has ____ imbibing power than proteins.</text>
            <option id="A">Lower</option><option id="B">Higher</option><option id="C">Equal</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proteins are much more hydrophilic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Phytochrome might influence stomata? Yes. But main hormone is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">ABA</option><option id="B">Auxin</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Abscisic acid primary control.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Loading in phloem ____ water potential inside sieve tubes.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreases</option><option id="B">Increases</option><option id="C">Matches</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Makes it more negative.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Movement in phloem and xylem are both types of ____ flow.</text>
            <option id="A">Bulk / Mass</option><option id="B">Solitary</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Different drive, similar aggregate movement.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Transpiration can provide minerals with ____ concentration in leaves compared to roots.</text>
            <option id="A">Higher (Accumulation)</option><option id="B">Lower</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water leaves, minerals stay.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pressure potential is also called ____ pressure in a cell.</text>
            <option id="A">Turgor</option><option id="B">Osmotic</option><option id="C">Negative</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Force on wall.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The phenomenon of water being pulled by evaporation is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Transpiration Pull</option><option id="B">Suction head</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Main water lifting force.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is water potential affected by atmospheric pressure?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (Standard is 0, higher pressure increases it)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Physics of solution energy.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Relative humidity 100% means transpiration will ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Stop completely (usually)</option><option id="B">Skyrocket</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>No gradient for evaporation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cavitation refers to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Breaking of water column in xylem</option><option id="B">Plant growth</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formation of gas bubbles due to tension.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Diffusion occurs only in ____ substances?</text>
            <option id="A">Gases and Liquids mostly</option><option id="B">Solids only</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Requires molecular motion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Molecules move in a ____ manner in diffusion.</text>
            <option id="A">Random / Kinetic</option><option id="B">Linear</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Net movement to low concentration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Unit of Water Potential in physics is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Pascal (Pa)</option><option id="B">Mole</option><option id="C">Joule</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pressure units.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In isotonic solution, net flow of water is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Zero (Zero gain/loss)</option><option id="B">Unidirectional</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Equilibrium state.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Symplastic movement is ____ due to cytoplasmic streaming.</text>
            <option id="A">Relatively fast over short distances</option><option id="B">Always slow</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Helped by metabolic activity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Apoplast transport ____ traverse membranes.</text>
            <option id="A">Does not</option><option id="B">Does</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs outside living cell part.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mycorrhiza provides ____ to the plant and gets ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Minerals/Water , Sugar</option><option id="B">Sugar , Minerals</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Classic symbiosis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Movement of water into xylem is mostly ____ in humid conditions? No. Root pressure dominated.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes, in absence of transpiration</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Allows small plant transport.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Last check: Transport in plants chapter 120 questions reached?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">Maybe</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
    </hard>
</chapter>
